  <h1>Common Divorce Settlement Misconceptions</h1>
  <p><em>Reviewed by Aspen Lockwood (AL), Editor-in-Chief. Updated May 2026.</em></p>
  <h2>&ldquo;Everything gets split 50/50.&rdquo;</h2><p>Only in the nine community property states, and even there, the 50/50 rule applies to marital property &mdash; not separate property. In equitable distribution states, the split depends on income, contributions, and other factors. Outcomes of 60/40 or 65/35 are common in long marriages with large income gaps.</p>
  <h2>&ldquo;Adultery will win me more money.&rdquo;</h2><p>In most states, fault has little or no effect on property division. Some states allow fault to affect alimony. The trend in modern family law is no-fault divorce where marital misconduct is largely irrelevant to financial outcomes.</p>
  <h2>&ldquo;My spouse can&rsquo;t touch my 401(k).&rdquo;</h2><p>The portion accrued during the marriage is marital property and subject to division via QDRO in virtually every state. Only the portion accrued before the marriage (and kept genuinely separate) is protected as separate property.</p>
  <h2>&ldquo;Alimony is forever.&rdquo;</h2><p>Permanent alimony is rare and increasingly disfavored. Modern family law favors rehabilitative alimony &mdash; support while the recipient retains or improves earning capacity. Long-term alimony for long marriages is still awarded but often capped at 5&ndash;10 years except in extraordinary circumstances.</p>
  <h2>&ldquo;If I move out, I lose the house.&rdquo;</h2><p>Not automatically. Moving out of the marital home during the divorce does not forfeit your property rights in it. Courts divide the home as a marital asset regardless of who is living there during the proceedings. However, moving out may affect temporary custody arrangements.</p>
  <h2>Where to go from here</h2>
